ce:section.ce:para:
In addition to the numerical model simplification, various assumptions are adopted for the TES unit, including the following:

                              (1)

The open-celled metal foam is homogeneous in each filling area;


                              (2)

The liquid phase PCM is a Newtonian fluid satisfying the Boussinesq assumption, producing buoyancy force due to density changes with temperature;


                              (3)

The paraffin phase change process experiences no change in thermophysical parameters and volume, and natural convection is in the laminar flow regime;


                              (4)

Thermal energy exchange between the model and the externalities is ignored, an adiabatic boundary condition is set, and the contact thermal resistance is regarded as zero between the circulating fluid and the tube, the tube and the paraffin, and the PCM in each region;


                              (5)

Inlet and outlet conditions of HTF (water) remain constant.

In the formulas (7) and (8): ρ water, λ water, μwater and T water represent the density, thermal conductivity, dynamic viscosity, and temperature of water, in respective; u water, v water, and w water donate the direction velocity components of x, y and z, respectively; λ tube and T tube exhibit the heat conductivity and temperature of the copper tube;
U →
accounts for the velocity vector; g is acceleration of gravity.
